		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30005977">Actually, I would say that Pokemon is Magical Realism than anything else. So the person who wrote the question is <em>objectively</em> wrong there.<br />
<br />
If one was to stick strictly to semantics, I would say that I rather like this definition: <a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SliceOfLife" target="_blank" rel="nofollow"><a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SliceOfLife" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SliceOfLife</a></a><br />
<br />
In particular, it says something that I quite agree with. "What separates slice of life as a genre from the literal meaning of the phrase (which would encompass nearly all fiction) is the emphasis on the very moment, with the intent of focusing the audience on that moment rather than using that moment as part of a narrative...<br />
<br />
Slice of Life series don't usually have much of a plot or, if taken to extreme, even the omnipresent Conflict, but they don't really need one, and many Slice of Life stories use a lack of conflict to serve peaceful escapism rather than realism. An example of this would be how in many slice of life school stories, parents are nearly non-existent. Most American newspaper comics that aren't simply gag a day strips are stories like this due to the simple fact that most people do not read newspapers every day and archives of comic strips are rare, so they need to be able to jump into the comic's world at any time and be able to appreciate it."<br />
<br />
So, essentially, I would consider it a sub-genre of realism, in which characters partake in activities that may or may have meaning, narrative substance, or really any logical sequences. Which is why some gags border on the slice of life genre, since some arguably do use these so-called mundane activities for some purpose rather than the fleeing moment itself. As such, the most prototypical (albeit the most exceptional) SOL would be Aria the Animation, Natural, and Origination, since they really illustrate what can be done with the genre.<br />
<br />
Mundane events can go one of many ways. And in the cases that it focuses more on the "the very moment, with the intent of focusing the audience on that moment rather than using that moment as part of a narrative," then it would be SOL; in the case that it emphasizes the comical aspects of the narrative, then it would be comedy; in the case that it emphatically or substantially focuses on the drama, then drama; if the boundaries are indefinite (for instance-- a show with 12 episodes, 6 of which are evidently drama-focused, and the other 6 patently SOL), then usually it can be labelled as two of the genres or more.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
