		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30078357"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>Mamimii said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>Genres are vague in general, so SoL isn't unique in that sense. <br />
<br />
It might also be more accurate to call the genre 'Slice of Daily Life' because every anime that features characters shows their lives—but, of course, that's not what SoL refers to. To me, SoL implies, at the very least, a relatively unchanging state of normalcy and complete non-emergency.<!--quote--></div><br />
This I find myself agreeing with.<br />
Though I also associate SOL with a feeling. Not in terms of relaxation, but I guess in terms of what Mamimii says " a relatively unchanging state of normalcy and complete non-emergency."<br />
<br />
As the influence of other genres rises (ie, more comedy, more drama, more romance) then the SOL feeling lessens and it's not really one anymore. <br />
<br />
It is vague in its application to some shows. To others it is so clearly SOL more than anything else (Aria).</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
