		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30088261"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>RMNDolphy said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>But Aria's setting is firmly sci-fi and so much of the show (particularly The Natural) is focused around this setting; couldn't it be considered sci-fi, perhaps even predominately so? It even has fantasy elements, with stuff like giant bipedal cats. Maybe even a coming of age story! <span style="font-size: 50%;">(Is that even a genre?)<!--size--></span><br />
<br />
What gives slice of life dominance over these other genres? What tangible benefit is there to categorizing it this way? Isn't that ultimately reducing what the anime is into a snippy, inaccurate word? Isn't it devaluing in a way? Surely there's a lot more to Aria than "slice of life".<br />
<br />
totes highjacking this thread to discuss the point of genres.<!--quote--></div>Well, IMO you make a mistake here, in that whether or not Simo unwittingly suggested Aria is 'more SoL than anything' is utterly irrelevant to 'the point of genres': you don't have to choose one single genre to describe a story. You could say 'Aria is sci-fi, fantasy, slice of life and even coming of age' and it would be a fine description. <br />
<br />
For the sake of characterising Aria, I consider it more fantasy than science fiction as its setting is by and large more imaginative than innovative. Sure, as you said in your original post, a one-paragraph synopsis is better and less controversial to give a specific idea of the work by itself. It is, however, not better for the purpose of comparing and grouping it with other works, which is most definitely not just a 'weird compulsion' as you said but a very useful endeavour. Grouping works in genres helps finding thematically similar stories to see interesting tropes and ideas be explored further; it helps identifying trends in the way certain themes are approached; it creates expectations for authors to market <em>or subvert(!)</em>; it's a useful shorthand to avoid plot specifics while remaining accurate. <br />
<br />
The punchline is that genres are like ratings. They're not perfect, but they're more useful than harmful, which is the obvious reason why people use them.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
