		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30091155"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>lpf said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>RMNDolphy said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>But Aria's setting is firmly sci-fi and so much of the show (particularly The Natural) is focused around this setting; couldn't it be considered sci-fi, perhaps even predominately so? It even has fantasy elements, with stuff like giant bipedal cats. Maybe even a coming of age story! <span style="font-size: 50%;">(Is that even a genre?)<!--size--></span><br />
<br />
What gives slice of life dominance over these other genres? What tangible benefit is there to categorizing it this way? Isn't that ultimately reducing what the anime is into a snippy, inaccurate word? Isn't it devaluing in a way? Surely there's a lot more to Aria than "slice of life".<br />
<br />
totes highjacking this thread to discuss the point of genres.<!--quote--></div>Well, IMO you make a mistake here, in that whether or not Simo unwittingly suggested Aria is 'more SoL than anything' is utterly irrelevant to 'the point of genres': you don't have to choose one single genre to describe a story. You could say 'Aria is sci-fi, fantasy, slice of life and even coming of age' and it would be a fine description. <br />
<br />
For the sake of characterising Aria, I consider it more fantasy than science fiction as its setting is by and large more imaginative than innovative. Sure, as you said in your original post, a one-paragraph synopsis is better and less controversial to give a specific idea of the work by itself. It is, however, not better for the purpose of comparing and grouping it with other works, which is most definitely not just a 'weird compulsion' as you said but a very useful endeavour. Grouping works in genres helps finding thematically similar stories to see interesting tropes and ideas be explored further; it helps identifying trends in the way certain themes are approached; it creates expectations for authors to market <em>or subvert(!)</em>; it's a useful shorthand to avoid plot specifics while remaining accurate. <br />
<br />
The punchline is that genres are like ratings. They're not perfect, but they're more useful than harmful, which is the obvious reason why people use them.<!--quote--></div><br />
<br />
Well, I'd be the first to agree that, if pushed to call it something, Aria would be a slice of life. I just don't see the point. Identifying tropes to be explored further? What? To what end? That seems just as reductionistic to me. To continue with the Aria example, it certainly far more than the sum of its tropes. Identifying tropes and judging things based on them, even partially, suggests to me that anime criticism is based around comparison, which I can't agree with at all. It's too prone to phony axioms (x didn't do y (because of trope/genre expectations), therefore bad) and unfair comparisons between things that are fundamentally different in approach despite sharing 1 or 2 nebulous tropes. Even if one avoids these trappings, comparisons, even subconscious ones, are a piss poor way to go about things. <br />
<br />
The expectations for author to market point is a fair one. It's unfortunate and limiting, but it's easy to see why genres necessary for that. I can also sorta agree with the shorthand reason (I even mentioned it above), but even then I think you're doing the work a disservice. Telling someone interested in Aria that it it is a sci fi fantasy slice of life could mean anything. All of those genres are really broad and carry their own unfair expectations. Someone might think it's about dragons on spaceships just kicking it and taking it easy. That sounds super rad. I would be very disappointed with Aria if I came into it expecting that, and all I get is boring boat people, fashion that can't match Code Geass, and music that can't compare to LoGH :)<br />
<br />
All good posts contain jokes that like 4 people will get.<br />
<br />
Also, ratings <em>are</em> shit. They do more harm than good, but that's another topic entirely.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: right;"><!--link--><a href="http://drillmilkyholmes.wordpress.com/" rel="nofollow"><img src="http://i.imgur.com/7ALjX4f.png" /></a></div></td>
